   <activity estimated-time="5">
        <introduction>
            <p>
   Recall that a rational function is a ratio of two polynomials. For any given rational function, what are all the possible behaviors as <m>x</m> tends to + or - infinity?
            </p>
        </introduction>

            <ol label="A">
                <li><p>The only possible limit is 0</p></li>
                <li><p>The only possible limits are 0 or +/- infinity
 </p></li>
                <li><p>The only possible limits are 0, 1 or +/- infinity
 </p></li>
                <li><p>The only possible limits are any constant number or +/- infinity</p></li>
            </ol>
   
    </activity>        
    
<remark>
    <statement> In the long run a rational function behaves like a ratio of the leading terms of the numerator and denominator. So the rational function
        <me>
            r(x) =  \displaystyle\frac{5(x+2)(x+4)}{x^2+3x-4}
        </me>
behaves like the ratio <m>\frac{5x^2}{x^2}</m> and so as <m>x</m> tends to positive infinity, <m>r(x)</m> tends to 5.  
    </statement>
    </remark>

  
